environmental standard.DEF: The specification of the maximum acceptable limit for a pollutant with a safety margin to guarantee public safety.

EU office or agency.DEF: Established by the Treaties to exist alongside the institutions of the European Union.

sponsorship.DEF: The direct or indirect funding by persons or organisations of social, cultural, sporting or other activities or of their broadcasting.

EU sponsorship.DEF: Support provided by the European Union for cultural and sporting events in order to promote its image.

Mediterranean third countries.DEF: countries of the Southern Mediterranean and the Near and Middle East associated with the European Union through the Euro-Mediterranean partnership

Central and Eastern European countries.DEF: countries of Central and Eastern Europe associated with the EU through association agreements

tradeable emission permit.DEF: A permit that allows a certain source to emit a specified volume of some pollutant.  A permit is different from an allowance: the permit identifies the allowances that the site will receive, whereas allowances are the system's tradable unit.

multiannual financial framework.DEF: EU long-term spending plan that lays down the maximum annual amounts (‘ceilings’) which the EU may spend in different political fields (‘headings’) over a period of at least 5 years.

EU visa policy.DEF: EU Member States' shared policy on visas.

public accounting.DEF: The set of procedures governing the financial implementation and the recording of State and local-authority transactions.

Presidency of the Council of the EU.DEF: responsibility conferred on EU member states, that rotates every six months, for chairing meetings of the different Council configurations (with the exception of the Foreign Affairs Council) and the Council's preparatory bodies; organising formal and informal meetings, and representing the Council in its dealings with other EU institutions

principle of subsidiarity.DEF: Principle according to which the European Union takes action only when the objectives in question can be better achieved at EU level than at the level of the Member States.

confidence motion.DEF: Occasion when a government, on its own initiative, defends its record before parliament.

action for annulment (EU).DEF: Legal remedy which allows the Court of Justice of the EU to review the legality of acts adopted by the European institutions, bodies, offices or agencies and to repeal them if they are deemed to be in breach of EU law.

environmental tax.DEF: Tax which allows pollution or noise to be emitted or which rewards services for waste treatment or which is levied on products which are likely to pollute.

human rights.DEF: rights inherent to all human beings, regardless of race, sex, nationality, ethnicity, language, religion, or any other status

travel ban (EU).DEF: restrictive measure, consisting of denial of entry upon presentation at an external border of the EU, taken by a Member State under the Common Foreign and Security Policy to prevent a pre-identified, third-country national from entering or transiting through its territory

trans-European network.DEF: The interconnection and interoperability of national transport, telecommunications and energy networks aimed at creating an area without internal frontiers.

dumping.DEF: Act of selling goods abroad at prices lower than those on the domestic market.

air safety.DEF: According to the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO) terminology, ‘air safety’ is related to the operational safety of aircraft, including personnel licensing and airworthiness, whereas ‘aviation security’ means safeguarding civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference.

recognised non-citizen.DEF: person who is not a citizen of the reporting country nor of any other country, but who has established links to that country which include some but not all rights and obligations of full citizenship

security services.DEF: Sector that produces the goods and services required to protect citizens from insecurity.

multilateral surveillance.DEF: monitoring of economic developments in Member States and the EU as a whole carried out by the Council in order to ensure closer coordination of economic policies and sustained convergence of the economic performances of the Member States

financing level.DEF: Proportion of the costs of a project eligible for funding under EU financial instruments.

dual-use technology.DEF: Civilian technology which contains possibilities for military use.

processing under customs control.DEF: Procedure which allows non-EU goods to be processed without being subject to import duties or to trade policy measures. Products resulting from this processing are put on the market but are subject to the usual import duties.

AAMS countries.DEF: Associated African and Malagasy States, associated with the EEC by the first and second Yaoundé Conventions.

non-standard employment.DEF: Work which is other than full-time and permanent, including part-time, evening and weekend work, fixed-term work, teleworking and outwork.

seasonal employment.DEF: Work that, because of its nature or of factors peculiar to the industry in which it is performed, is available, at approximately the same time or times every year, for part or parts only of the year. This situation occurs particularly in agriculture and tourism.

group farming.DEF: Association of several farmers for the purpose of working together or making joint investments.

sensitive area.DEF: Area protected by special measures to preserve a highly vulnerable natural habitat.

cyclical unemployment.DEF: Unemployment due to variations in the business cycle.

hidden unemployment.DEF: The situation of a person who cannot be considered as unemployed since he is not looking for work. He is therefore no longer counted as part of the labour force.

seasonal unemployment.DEF: Employment rate variations linked to the time of year.

structural unemployment.DEF: Unemployment resulting from changes in the structure of the economy, technical progress, re-siting of industries or changes in the composition of the work force.

cinema.DEF: art of motion-picture photography and filming

allocation clause.DEF: Clause stating that lists which do not obtain a minimum percentage of votes, variable according to country, do not partake in the distribution of seats.

protective clause.DEF: Clause which authorises contracting parties to ignore certain provisions of an agreement if there is a threat to their essential interests.

advisory committee (EU).DEF: Committee responsible for issuing opinions on the implementing measures proposed by the Commission, operating in accordance with the advisory procedure laid down in Article 3 of the Comitology Decision.

food additive.DEF: Substances added intentionally to foodstuffs to perform certain technological functions, for example to colour, to sweeten or to help preserve foods. In the European Union all food additives are identified by an E number. The most common additives to appear on food labels are antioxidants (to prevent deterioration caused by oxidation), colours, emulsifiers, stabilisers, gelling agents and thickeners, preservatives and sweeteners.

EU Council committee.DEF: Council decisions are prepared by a structure of more than 150 working parties and committees comprising delegates from the Member States. They resolve technical issues and forward the dossier to the Permanent Representatives Committee (Coreper).

structural adjustment.DEF: Set of economic policy measures aimed at correcting a country's major imbalances by providing it with structures, operating mechanisms and a price system close to those currently in force in the world market, all aimed, in the long term, at re-orientating production and investment decisions.

audit.DEF: A methodical examination and review carried out to ascertain the general situation of a company or to assess whether a particular activity conforms with legal provisions or the rules of good management.

social clause.DEF: Incorporates those basic labour standards on which developed and developing countries agree. These standards apply to the right to organise trade unions, the right to collective bargaining, the banning of slavery and forced labour, non-discrimination and the minimum working age.

European Works Council.DEF: The European Works Council aims to improve the right to information and consultancy of employees working in EU-scale undertakings and groups of companies.

recognition of vocational training quali.DEF: Mutual recognition of certificates and other documents confirming completion of vocational training.

hazardous waste.DEF: Waste which must be handled with particular care in view of the possible risks of injury to humans, animals or the environment.

legal deposit.DEF: Handing over to the appropriate institutions of several free copies of a literary or audiovisual work on or after their publication.

social dumping.DEF: The practice of taking advantage of lower labour costs in certain countries (owing to lower social security and other contributions), thus attracting business away from other countries and thereby creating unfair competition.

established right.DEF: Right awarded under a former law.

territorial waters.DEF: Strip of water between coastline and open sea having a maximum width of 12 miles.

electronic publishing.DEF: The collection, organisation and distribution of all types of information on interactive magnetic and optical supports.

bovine spongiform encephalopathy.DEF: Bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) is a degenerative brain disease affecting bovine livestock.

economic intelligence.DEF: All the actions aimed at stimulating, disseminating and exploiting the results of research, technological development and demonstration (RTD) for the benefit and information of companies and other economic agents.

globalisation.DEF: Progressive integration of the global economy.

multimedia.DEF: Integration of sound, images (possibly animated) and text on a single support.

principle of proportionality.DEF: Principle in accordance with which the Commission, pursuant to the Amsterdam Protocol, proposes measures which are proportional to the aim pursued, allowing each Member State the largest possible margin for realising these measures on a national scale.

comparative advertising.DEF: Comparative advertising means any advertising which explicitly or by implication identifies a competitor or goods or services offered by a competitor.

information society.DEF: A society where a significant degree of activity focuses on the creation, distribution, use and reuse of information. This activity takes place by means information and communication technologies (ICTs).

economic transition.DEF: Reform of the political structures in a country or group of countries, resulting in the transition from a planned economy to a market economy.

euro area.DEF: Geographical area covering those Member States who have adopted the euro as their currency.

zoonosis.DEF: Infectious disease of animals which can be transmitted to humans.

Taric.DEF: Taric is used by the Commission and the Member States for the purpose of applying EU measures relating to imports and exports and to trade between Member States.

cloning.DEF: The production, by way of vegetative reproduction, of a group of cells or organisms which are genetic duplicates and thus genetically identical to the original stock or ancestral cell.

company in difficulties.DEF: company that is unable to stem losses which, without outside intervention by public authorities, will almost certainly condemn it to go out of business in the short or medium term

information highway.DEF: The entire spectrum of worldwide, interactive data transmission and reception, including internet, interactive television and similar networked media.

intranet.DEF: Internal telecommunications and computer-network system designed to be used exclusively within a particular organisation. The protocols and technologies used are based on Internet technology.

extranet.DEF: Telecommunications and computer network in the shape of an extended intranet system allowing communication with outside organisations, such as clients and suppliers.

browser.DEF: A client program which allows users to look for and read hypertext documents on the world wide web and navigate between them.

electronic document management.DEF: Refers to the complete range of equipment, software and technical means used in and for storing and archiving data in numerical form.

optical character recognition.DEF: The process of optical character recognition consists in the conversion, by means of a scanner or machine which recognises letters and characters through a mechanism of electronic conversion using a light source, of a numeric image into text, which can then subsequently be modified and processed by means of a word-processing programme.

digitisation.DEF: Conversion of analog data or signals into digital data or signals.

scanner.DEF: Computer peripheral for digitising text and image.

consolidated account.DEF: Financial statement combining the accounts of two or more companies in a group.

consumer policy.DEF: Policy aimed at defending the specific interests of consumers by recognising their fundamental rights and by aiming to reduce inequalities, fight against disloyal practices, promote health and safety and improve the standard of living in general.

EU policy - national policy.DEF: How European Union policy affects national policy and vice versa.

area of freedom, security and justice.DEF: Comprises activities carried out under the first pillar (free movement of persons, asylum, immigration, visas, judicial cooperation in civil matters) and the third pillar (police and judicial cooperation in criminal matters).

care for the elderly.DEF: Care that is designed to meet the needs and requirements of senior citizens at various stages.

virtual reality.DEF: A computer simulation of reality which uses 3D graphics to create a life-like environment.

picture synthesis.DEF: The creation, editing or publishing of pictures by means of a computer.

principle of communitisation.DEF: Communitisation means transferring a matter which, in the institutional framework of the Union, is dealt with using the intergovernmental method (second and third pillars) to the Community method (first pillar).

liability of the State.DEF: Principle according to which a Member State is considered liable for damages caused to individuals as a result of the infringement of EU law and is required to make reparations.

coaching in the workplace.DEF: continuous two-way feedback between the employee and the coach with the intention to work on areas for improvement and reinforce strengths to sustain the progress of the employee’s performance

special leave.DEF: Leave, other than annual leave, granted for family reasons, change of residence, training, etc.

enhanced cooperation.DEF: Principle which allows Member States who so wish to make progress at a different pace or on different objectives outside the institutional framework of the European Union.

hypermedia.DEF: The linking of multimedia to web documents; the integration of text, images, sound, graphics, animation and video through hyperlinks.

hypertext.DEF: Pages of computer text which are authored in software so as to allow extensive cross-referencing between related sections of text and associated graphic material.

opinion (EU).DEF: Opinions are non-binding legal acts adopted by the European institutions which do not bind those to whom they are addressed.

mode of production.DEF: The way in which a society goes about producing goods and services, consisting of the forces and relations of production.

prospective technological studies.DEF: The examination and evaluation of the possible consequences of the introduction of new technologies.

field research.DEF: Academic or other investigative study undertaken in a natural setting, rather than in laboratories, classrooms, or other structured environments.

European agricultural model.DEF: Model based on multifunctional, sustainable and competitive farming.

national school.DEF: Special school for the training of future police and fire officers, etc.

agricultural area with environmental res.DEF: An area where environmental factors must be taken into consideration before it is used for agricultural purposes.

agroforestry.DEF: The simultaneous growing of trees with food crops and/or livestock on the same piece of land.

crop rotation.DEF: The system of growing a sequence of different crops on the same ground so as to maintain or increase its fertility.

silo.DEF: A container, often cylindrical in shape, for the storage of grain.

ecology.DEF: Study of relations with the environment, mainly physical or geographical.

zootechnics.DEF: The science concerned with the domestication and breeding of animals.

forest certification.DEF: A procedure in which an independent third party awards a certificate attesting that a forest is being managed and used sustainably in accordance with agreed standards.

Euribor.DEF: Interbank interest rates calculated with the assistance of the European System Central Bank (ESCB).

econometrics.DEF: The application of mathematical and statistical techniques to economic problems and theories.

continuing vocational training.DEF: Term used in a general sense to designate any vocational training undertaken by a worker throughout his working life.

labour flexibility.DEF: The relaxation of labour regulations, which are considered to be one of the main impediments to growth and job creation. Includes flexibility regarding wages, working hours, the organisation of work and also the use of manpower through flexible job and location practices.

skill obsolescence.DEF: Professional qualifications which no longer meet the demand or which are no longer valid, owing to technological change, for example. This situation can be remedied through vocational retraining.

labour shortage.DEF: Situation where the number of job-seekers is inferior to the demand.

head-hunting.DEF: The recruitment by various methods of employees from one company to another, often rival, company.

demotion.DEF: The lowering in rank or position of a person, especially transferral to a poorer job.

non-participating country.DEF: A Member State which has not yet adopted the single currency, either intentionally or because it does not yet meet the conditions.

participating country.DEF: A Member State which has adopted the single currency.

resistance of materials.DEF: The study of the mechanical properties of materials and the conditions under which they resist or deform when used.

benchmarking.DEF: series of simple and transparent points of reference which, by means of tests, can help to monitor trends in competitiveness over a period of time, while at the same time offering a base from which to set targets and adopt the plans needed to attain them

non-lethal weapon.DEF: Weapons specifically designed to incapacitate combattants and equipment, while at the same time minimising the risk of death, permanent injury and irreversible damage to property and the environment.

service concession.DEF: act attributable to the State whereby a public authority entrusts to a third party – by means of a contractual act or a unilateral act with the prior consent of the third party – the total or partial management of services for which that authority would normally be responsible and for which the third party assumes the risk

commercial contract.DEF: A contract which in terms of form, nature or type of signatory constitutes a commercial act.

services of general interest.DEF: market and non-market services which the public authorities class as being of general interest and subject to specific public service obligations

electronic signature.DEF: Data in electronic form which are attached to or logically associated with other electronic data and which serve as a method of authentication.

exclusion from an international organisa.DEF: Sanction imposed on a country as the result of a dispute between an international organisation and one or more countries, or between two or more international organisations.

Union for the Mediterranean.DEF: intergovernmental organisation that promotes cooperation and dialogue in the Euro-Mediterranean region through initiatives addressing the three strategic objectives of regional stability, human development and regional economic integration

aid evaluation.DEF: Independent and objective examination of the pertinence, effectiveness, efficiency, impact and viability of a humanitarian intervention, in order to draw appropriate conclusions.

anti-personnel weapon.DEF: Refers to weapons and devices used against persons, not against equipment.

agricultural economics.DEF: study of the allocation, distribution and utilisation of the resources used, along with the commodities produced, by farming

astronautics.DEF: The science and technology of space flight.

bioclimatology.DEF: The study of the influences exerted on living organisms by climate.

soil chemistry.DEF: Branch of soil science concerned with the chemical composition, properties and reactions of soils.

cultural geography.DEF: The study of the relationship between geography and cultural.

human geography.DEF: The study of man's geographical distribution and spatial organisation.

regional geography.DEF: The study of the characteristics of a region and their economic, ecological or social implications.

geomorphology.DEF: The branch of geology that is concerned with the structure, origin, and development of the topographical features of the earth's crust.

sedimentology.DEF: The branch of geology concerned with sedimentary rocks and deposits.

ethnography.DEF: The branch of anthropology that deals with the scientific description of individual human societies.

industrial sociology.DEF: Sociology applied to the world of work, e.g. the workplace as a social system, occupational status, racial and intergroup relations in the enterprise, etc.

concerted economic action.DEF: Cooperation between the State and undertakings with a view to taking economic decisions jointly.

reduction of gas emissions.DEF: policies and measures to reduce the emissions or enhance the sinks of greenhouse gases so as to mitigate the effects of climate change

acidification.DEF: The acidification of water, soil and vegetation by the deposition of acidifying pollutants (sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides and ammonia).

remote patient monitoring.DEF: technology to enable monitoring of patients outside of conventional clinical settings

economies of scale.DEF: Reduction of production costs of a unit owing to an increase in its production capacity.

transport economics.DEF: Study of transport requirements and the most appropriate ways in which to meet them.

controlled economy.DEF: An economy in which the State intervenes but does not impose centralised planning.

stepfamily.DEF: A family into which one or both of the adult partners bring children from a previous relationship.

diaspora.DEF: The dispersion of people originally belonging to one nation or having a common culture.

generation renewal.DEF: The process of renewal whereby losses in a population due to deaths are replaced by births.

domestic violence.DEF: any form of physical, sexual or psychological violence which puts the safety or welfare of a family member at risk and/or the use of physical or emotional force or threat of physical force, including sexual violence, within the family or household

cultural exception.DEF: Political principle according to which cultural goods and services, by virtue of how they relate to culture, are of a specific nature which goes beyond the purely commercial and are not subject to free trade movements.

agri-foodstuffs.DEF: All activities involved in the preparation of foodstuffs, comprising production, preserving, processing and distribution.

food safety.DEF: Hygiene of food at all stages of the production process, from the primary production stage (mainly farming, hunting or fishing) to the final consumer.

palliative care.DEF: Nursing and medical care provided to terminally ill patients.

self-regulation.DEF: The practice of an organisation or group of like organisations voluntarily selecting, adopting and enforcing rules to produce compliance with a defined level of behaviour, without direct legislative interference by government.

underground economy.DEF: Sector of the economy based on illicit working or illegal activities which do not appear in the national statistics.

arbitration.DEF: The hearing and determination of a dispute, especially an industrial dispute, by an impartial referee selected or agreed upon by the parties concerned.

repeal.DEF: The official annulment or rescindment (as of a law or sentence) from operation or effect.

ecosystem.DEF: An ecological community considered together with the non-living factors of its environment as a unit.

agro-industry.DEF: All industrial activities involved in the processing of products of agricultural origin.

twin transition.DEF: simultaneous transition to a more sustainable and digital society

industrial integration.DEF: Mechanisms which ensure that industries of different countries complement each other in an attempt to achieve economic integration.

common security and defence policy.DEF: Policy which aims to safeguard the common values and fundamental interests of the Union and of its Member States and to preserve and strengthen peace.

comparative education.DEF: Comparative study of educational theories and practices in various countries.

hazard science.DEF: The science of danger, which studies natural, technological or domestic risks and their prevention.

cosmology.DEF: The branch of astronomy concerned with the evolution and structure of the universe.

assisting spouse.DEF: spouse of people who are engaged in work, usually of a self-employed or independent nature, but not necessarily receiving direct remuneration for it and often not entitled to social protection benefits

casual employment.DEF: Occasional or irregular work during peak periods or when other employees are absent.

basic education.DEF: The teaching of the elementary skills that pupils need to become productive citizens capable of civic engagement and sustaining competitive employment.

help for victims.DEF: The objective of help for victims is to inform victims and their families of their rights, advise them on procedures to be taken and offer them psychological support at all stages of the legal process.

hooliganism.DEF: Boorish, often violent behaviour by noisy, rough groups of persons, sometimes causing damage to property in public places or at sporting events.

vandalism.DEF: Intentional, needless damage and destruction, especially of public buildings and places.

eugenics.DEF: The study of methods of improving the quality of the human race, especially by selective breeding.

working poor.DEF: The working poor are households with an income below the poverty line.

entrepreneurship.DEF: A readiness to embark on new social or business ventures.

corporate governance.DEF: The organisation of power within a company or business so as to achieve a better balance between management, auditors and shareholders.

social labelling.DEF: Labels providing an assurance about the social and ethical impact of a business process on other stakeholders.

company buyout.DEF: The purchase of a company, especially by its former management or staff, sometimes with outside backing from a bank or other institution.

reintegration enterprise.DEF: A manufacturing or service business set up specifically to facilitate the reintegration of unemployed people through the exercise of an economic activity.

start-up.DEF: Company initiated by individual founders or entrepreneurs to search for a repeatable and scalable business model.

non-formal education.DEF: Activities or programmes organised outside of the school system but directed towards precise educational objectives.

disinformation.DEF: information that is deliberately false or ambiguous with the intention of influencing the opinions of those who receive it

Internet access provider.DEF: An organisation or business offering public access to the Internet.

malware.DEF: any software designed to disrupt, damage, leak, gain  unauthorized access or deprive access to information, a computer, computer network, or an IT system malign software that is designed to disrupt, damage, or gain unauthorised access to a computer or IT system and which may use networks to spread

basic needs.DEF: The minimum food, clothing and housing needs of a human being.

region-EU relationship.DEF: The position of the regions and their influence on the various European policies.

social transfers.DEF: The transfer of income and public service provision to individuals and social groups without payment so that they can enjoy an improved standard of living.

economic value.DEF: The economic and measurable character of a good or service, taking into account its cost and offer and demand.

food supplement.DEF: Concentrated sources of nutrients or other substances with a nutritional or physiological effect, whose purpose is to supplement the normal diet. Food supplements are marketed 'in dose' form, for example as pills, tablets, capsules or liquids in measured doses etc.

health education.DEF: Instructing the general public in the basic principles of health and hygiene.

special education.DEF: Form of education for pupils with special needs, such as the mentally or physically handicapped.

game theory.DEF: branch of applied mathematics that provides tools for analysing situations in which parties, called players, make decisions that are interdependent. This interdependence causes each player to consider the other player’s possible decisions, or strategies, in formulating strategy

intelligent transport system.DEF: The application of telematics in transport.

ground handling.DEF: This covers all services connected with an aircraft, such as refuelling and maintenance, and passenger, baggage and cargo handling.

oligarchy.DEF: Government by a small group of people.

nationalist party.DEF: A party which extols national pride, sometimes possessing xenophobic or isolationist tendencies.

governance.DEF: Governance refers to the process whereby elements in society wield power and authority, and influence and enact policies and decisions concerning public life.

early-stage capital.DEF: Money used for the initial investment in a project or startup company, for proof-of-concept, market research, or initial product development.

dropout.DEF: Students and trainees who, for reasons of inaptitude, financial problems, etc., do not complete an organised period of training.

popularising science.DEF: The adaptation of scientific and technical knowledge to make it accessible to non-specialists.

knowledge management.DEF: Knowledge management involves the identification and analysis of available and required knowledge assets and knowledge asset related processes, and the subsequent planning and control of actions to develop both the assets and the processes so as to fulfil organisational objectives.

outsourcing.DEF: Outsourcing is when a company purchases a product or process from an outside supplier rather than producing in house.

telemedicine.DEF: delivery of health-related services and clinical care remotely by means of electronic information and communication technologies

child development.DEF: biological, psychological and emotional changes that occur in human beings between birth and the conclusion of adolescence

transhumanism.DEF: belief or theory that the human race can progress beyond its current physical and mental limitations, especially by means of science and technology

European Constitution.DEF: Draft Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe (Not ratified).

universal service.DEF: A defined minimum service of a specified quality available to all users and consumers in the Union and, taking into account specific national conditions, at an affordable price.

International Criminal Tribunal.DEF: The International Criminal Tribunal is empowered to prosecute persons responsible for serious violations of international humanitarian law on a defined territory (e.g. the “International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia”, the “International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda”).

vision of Europe.DEF: Philosophical and historical perspective of a united Europe.

disruptive technology.DEF: technology that causes a relevant change and abruptly interrupts the way in which industries, companies, and consumers operate constitutes a disruptive innovation

political cohabitation.DEF: This term originated in the 1980s when the socialist French President, Franþois Mitterrand, was forced to adopt a power-sharing solution when a government of the right was elected. The term is now also used to describe similar situations in other countries.

International Criminal Court.DEF: An independent, permanent court which tries persons accused of the most serious crimes of international concern, namely genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes.

geographical information system.DEF: Information system for use in decision-making in several domains, most of which relate to the human use of the physical environment.

European Agency for Reconstruction.DEF: Agency responsible for managing the European Union's main assistance programmes in Serbia and Montenegro (the Republic of Serbia, Kosovo and the Republic of Montenegro) and the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia.

One Health approach.DEF: collaborative, inter- and transdisciplinary way of working that recognises the interconnectedness of human, animal, plant and environmental health and aims to achieve optimal health outcomes by addressing the complex relationships and interdependencies between these systems

right to disconnect.DEF: right to disconnect from work and primarily not to engage in work-related electronic communication such as emails, calls or messages during non-work hours

balance of payments assistance.DEF: Medium-term EU financial assistance provided to non-euro area Member States facing serious balance-of-payments difficulties.

designated employment.DEF: Principle by which certain types of occupation are specially designated for the handicapped and must be reserved for them.

citizen's duties.DEF: obligations that are required of citizens by law and responsibilities that benefit the community and common good

territorial enclave.DEF: Territory or territorial unit administratively attached to an authority or state with which it is not contiguous.

ecological connectivity.DEF: ability for animals on land or in water to move freely from place to place, to find food, breed and establish new home territories

administrative offence.DEF: The breaking of a binding administrative regulation, normally incurring an administrative penalty.

foreign aid.DEF: Aid from the viewpoint of the donor country.

hinge party.DEF: Independent political force of the right or left which forms coalitions with the right or left.

EU borrowing.DEF: The EU is empowered by the EU Treaty to adopt borrowing programmes to mobilise the financial resources necessary to fulfill its mandate.

non-contributory benefit.DEF: Benefit awarded to needy persons who do not possess sufficient funds to maintain themselves and who have either never paid social security contributions or have not paid them for long enough to receive the benefits normally due to a wage-earner.

living will.DEF: A health care directive that tells others how a person would like to be treated if they lose their capacity to make decisions about health care. The term living will is often used when a person is planning for their last illness, but a health care directive can be made in any circumstances.

biometrics.DEF: The study of biological data by means of statistical analysis, used to positively determine a person's identity.

wave energy.DEF: Energy produced by the movement of waves.

soft energy.DEF: Energy which is non-pollutant, whether renewable or not.

business-to-consumer.DEF: business or transactions conducted directly between a company and consumers who are the end-users of its products or services

intellectual capital.DEF: totality of the intellectual resources and skills available for a business activity including worker competencies, intellectual property and customer satisfaction

judicial review.DEF: Investigation by a court of the legality of decisions taken by a subordinate body.

open method of coordination.DEF: Method of defining and adopting guidelines and common objectives, drawing up indicators and identifying best practice in areas where the EU has no powers, shares competence or has the power to undertake support measures.

public-private partnership.DEF: Cooperation between public authorities and private businesses for the purpose of carrying out infrastructure projects or providing public utilities.

digital divide.DEF: Disparities between individuals, households, businesses and geographical areas at various socioeconomic levels with regard to access to information technology and use of the Internet for a wide range of activities.

language policy.DEF: Administrative or legislative measures adopted to regulate or promote the use of one or more languages.

corporate social responsibility.DEF: Voluntary efforts by businesses to incorporate social and environmental concerns into their corporate activities and their relations with interested parties.

unsolicited electronic advertising.DEF: Unsolicited messages sent by electronic means for the purpose of direct marketing.

organisational culture.DEF: System of beliefs and values common to the members of a given organisation that guides their behaviour.

outplacement.DEF: Measures taken by an employer to help employees threatened with redundancy to find new jobs in other companies.

knowledge economy.DEF: Economy based on knowledge and technological innovation leading to the creation of a network of expertise.

conference of presidents.DEF: Conference comprising the presidents or chairmen of the parliamentary groups.

stem cell.DEF: Undifferentiated cell from an embryo, a foetus or adult tissues that is capable of dividing, differentiating into other cell types and multiplying in culture.

technical barriers to trade.DEF: obstacles to trade, such as technical regulations, standards, and conformity assessment procedures

customs warehouse.DEF: Place where imported goods or goods for export can be stored or processed without payment of customs duties.

working conditions.DEF: Physical, social and managerial factors affecting a worker's job.

European undertaking.DEF: Contractual partnership between the European Commission and the private sector.

bio-based product.DEF: fully or partially made from biological resources, rather than fossil raw materials

Chechen question.DEF: Conflict between the Russian government and various Chechen nationalist and Islamist forces.

epidemic.DEF: Intensive outbreaks or periods of unusually high incidence of disease in a community or area.

mutual assistance.DEF: Principle of international law which means that two or more countries agree to cooperate in a specific field.

blog.DEF: An online diary or a personal chronological log of thoughts which is maintained and updated regularly by an Internet user.

political culture.DEF: The values, traditions, attitudes and strategies associated with the way in which politics is conducted.

direct democracy.DEF: Constitutional system involving government by the people without recourse to elections. Source: UNTERM, United Nations Multilingual Terminology Database [online], http://unterm.un.org/ (Consulted on 8 September 2011)

European private law.DEF: Europeanisation of the civil law of the EU Member States.

civil society.DEF: All non-profit movements and associations which are independent of the State and whose objective is to transform, through concerted effort, the social policies, standards and structures at national and international level.

europeanisation.DEF: Process of incorporating the political and economic dynamics of the EU into the drafting of national policy.

geodesy.DEF: Science of determining the shape, size and field of gravity of the earth.

Frontex.DEF: European Agency for the Management of Operational Cooperation at the External Borders of the Member States of the European Union.

national identity.DEF: Set of ideas based on the concept of a nation and the identification of individuals or communities with those ideas.

succession of states.DEF: Replacement of one state by the rights and obligations of another as a result of complete incorporation or partial annexation of the state, division of the state or the creation of a new state. Source: UNTERM, United Nations Multilingual Terminology Database [online], http://unterm.un.org (Consulted on 8 September 2011).

recognition of a state.DEF: Act by which one or more states or an international institution declare or tacitly admit that the following is a state with the rights and obligations which this entails: a political group which actually exists and considers itself to be a state or a collective body of people who did not previously constitute an independent political organisation. Source: UNTERM, United Nations Multilingual Terminology Database [online], http://unterm.un.org (Consulted on 8 September 2011).

single payment scheme.DEF: Payment of European subsidies tied to the farm and not to production.

appointment of members.DEF: Appointment of the members of an institution, body or agency of the EU.

public policy.DEF: Action taken by a public authority to bring about social change in the medium and long term. It is based on certain values and objectives and is implemented using a variety of methods. It applies on the territory within which the authority is authorised to act.

ecological tourism.DEF: Form of tourism practised in areas of natural interest which are little affected by man in order to encourage an appreciation of biodiversity and cultural events, respect for the environment and the protection of flora and fauna.

equitable tourism.DEF: Form of tourism which promotes the protection and enhancement of the natural, cultural and human environment. It draws on concepts of sustainable development and is of socioeconomic benefit to local and regional communities.

European Union method.DEF: decision-making procedure that allows for a transparent, effective and democratic functioning of the European Union

CoR opinion.DEF: The Committee of the Regions issues technical opinions on regional matters. The Committee delivers mandatory opinions where the Treaty so provides. It may also be consulted whenever Parliament, the Commission or the Council deems it necessary, even when this is not provided for by the Treaty. Opinions are used to guide these institutions in their legislative activity and are not binding.

European Globalisation Adjustment Fund.DEF: The EGF aims to help workers made redundant as a result of changing global trade patterns to find another job as quickly as possible.

ergonomics.DEF: The study of the relationship between workers and their environment, especially the equipment they use.

discounting.DEF: Operation in which a negotiable instrument is purchased at a discount on its face value representing interest on the amount up to the maturity date.

institution of public utility.DEF: Private body whose activities are recognised as being in the public interest.

gold-exchange standard.DEF: International monetary system, elaborating on the pure gold standard, in which gold is an international currency alongside one or more key currencies, convertibility into gold being limited to key currencies.

gold standard.DEF: International monetary system in which each unit of currency is worth a fixed amount of gold.

Welfare State.DEF: Society in which welfare and social security are provided by the State through its departments and agencies.

Eurocurrency.DEF: National currency held by foreign companies or banks and traded on the international money market.

Eurodollar.DEF: Dollars which are held by banks or companies outside the United States and traded on the international money market.

financial incentive.DEF: money or benefit that a person, company or organisation offers to encourage certain behaviours or actions that may not otherwise have occurred

eutrophication.DEF: The enrichment of fresh or salt water by nutrients, causing an accelerated growth of algae and other plants which leads to a deterioration in the water quality.

nuclear accident.DEF: Event occurring in a nuclear power plant or anywhere that radioactive materials are used, stored, or transported.

education admission requirements.DEF: conditions of entrance to an educational institution, courses of study, further study, training

tax avoidance.DEF: Reduction or minimisation of tax liability by lawful means.

exclusion from treatment (EU).DEF: Authorisation granted by the Commission to Member States to derogate from EU standards with respect to the common commercial policy.

brain drain.DEF: Emigration of qualified persons to a country or region which offers them better working conditions.

removal.DEF: The enforcement of the obligation to return, namely the physical transportation out of the country.

business-to-government.DEF: business model where a business sells products, services, or information to a government body

amino acid.DEF: water-soluble organic compound that possesses both a carboxyl and an amino group attached to the same carbon atom

type of tenure.DEF: Relationship between the landowner and the farmer who works the land.

owner farming.DEF: Cultivation of an agricultural area by the landowner himself.

mixed tenure.DEF: Intermediate stage between owner farming and tenant farming.

private aid.DEF: Aid provided by churches, foundations, etc.

temporary admission.DEF: Entry for a limited period, with suspension of customs duties, of goods intended for re-export.

tenant farming.DEF: Arrangement under which a landowner lets land to a farmer in return for an annual payment not dependent on the yield from the farm.

soft power.DEF: ability to obtain the outcomes one wants by attraction and persuasion rather than by coercion

subsidiary.DEF: A company controlled directly or indirectly by another company, known as the parent or holding company.

joint subsidiary.DEF: A company set up jointly by two or more parent companies which themselves remain legally and financially independent.

performance measurement.DEF: Regular measurement of outcomes and results, which generates reliable data on the effectiveness and efficiency of an individual, a group, an organization, a system or a program.

European Banking Authority.DEF: One of the three European Supervisory Authorities forming part of the European System of Financial Supervision (ESFS) which works to ensure effective and consistent prudential regulation and supervision across the European banking sector.

autonomous vehicle.DEF: vehicle that uses computer sensing equipment to navigate with little or no human input

health determinant.DEF: Circumstances in which people are born, grow up, live, work, and age, as well as the systems put in place to deal with illness.

public data.DEF: Data produced by public sector bodies of the Member States, including executive, legislative and judicial bodies.

European Stability Mechanism.DEF: The European Stability Mechanism is the permanent crisis resolution mechanism for the countries of the euro area. The ESM issues debt instruments in order to finance loans and other forms of financial assistance to euro area Members States.

internally displaced person.DEF: Persons or groups of persons who have been forced or obliged to flee or to leave their homes or places of habitual residence, in particular as a result of or in order to avoid the effects of armed conflict, situations of generalized violence, violations of human rights or natural or human-made disasters, and who have not crossed an internationally recognized State border.

language skills.DEF: Skills combining knowledge and understanding with practice in language use, generally consisting of listening, speaking, reading and writing.

fracking.DEF: Process of injecting liquid at high pressure into subterranean rocks, boreholes, etc. so as to force open existing fissures and extract oil or gas.

financial audit.DEF: An independent assessment, resulting in a 'reasonable assurance' opinion, of whether an entity’s reported financial condition, results and use of resources are presented fairly in accordance with the financial reporting framework.

collective redress.DEF: Procedural mechanism which allows, for reasons of procedural economy and/or efficiency of enforcement, a number of individual claims relating to the same case to be bundled into a single court action. Collective redress is a broad concept that includes injunctive relief (lawsuits seeking to stop illegal behaviour) and compensatory relief (lawsuits seeking damages for harm caused).

long-term care.DEF: The activities undertaken by others to ensure that people with a significant ongoing loss of intrinsic capacity can maintain a level of functional ability consistent with their basic rights, fundamental freedoms and human dignity.

conspiracy theory.DEF: belief that certain events or situations are secretly manipulated behind the scenes by powerful forces with negative intent

Islamic finance.DEF: A financial system managing money in accordance with the Islamic law.

human development.DEF: Process of expanding the richness of human life rather than simply the richness of the economy in which human beings live.

circular economy.DEF: Model of economy which minimises waste through reusing, repairing, refurbishing and recycling existing materials and products.

Baltic Sea region.DEF: Covers eight EU countries (Sweden, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland).

wifi.DEF: Technology allowing computers, smartphones, or other devices to connect to the Internet or communicate with one another wirelessly within a particular area.

private equity.DEF: Provision of equity capital by financial investors to non-quoted companies with high growth potential.

green public procurement.DEF: Process whereby public authorities seek to procure goods, services and works with a reduced environmental impact throughout their life cycle.

functional food.DEF: Food that provides medical or health benefits.

foster parent.DEF: Adult that provides the care of a child without being the child’s parent or relative, or having parental responsibility for him.

option contract.DEF: An option is a financial instrument that gives the owner the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell specific assets (e.g. a bond or a stock) at a predetermined price (the strike or exercise price) at or up to a certain future date (the exercise or maturity date).

ecodesign.DEF: EU environmental requirements for energy-related products.

citizen science.DEF: Participation of the citizens in the scientific research process in different possible ways: as observers, as funders, in identifying images or analysing data, or providing data themselves.

3G.DEF: Mobile systems which provide access, by means of one or more radio links, to a wide range of telecommunications services supported by the fixed telecommunication networks and to other services which are specific to mobile users.

public licence.DEF: license by which a licensor can grant additional copyright permissions to all persons in the general public

machine-readable data.DEF: information encoded in a form which can be read (i.e., scanned/sensed) by a machine/computer and interpreted by the machine's hardware and/or software

food fraud.DEF: Violation of food law, which is committed intentionally to pursue an economic or financial gain through consumer deception.

EU restrictive measure.DEF: Sanction or restrictive measure applied by the European Union against the government of a third country, a non-State entity or an individual in pursuit of the specific objectives of the Common Foreign and Security Policy.

care economy.DEF: sector of economy that is responsible for the provision of care and services that contribute to the nurturing of current and future populations

e-invoicing.DEF: Any method by which an invoice is electronically presented to a customer for payment.

patient.DEF: person who is receiving medical care or treatment

open innovation.DEF: Process in which companies, public research institutions, financial institutions interact through the exchange of skills, knowledge and ideas for creating new products.

interbank market.DEF: The market for short-term lending between banks, usually involving the trading of funds with a maturity of between one day (overnight or even shorter) and one year.

multi-level governance.DEF: Coordinated action by the European Union, the Member States and local and regional authorities, based on partnership and aimed at drawing up and implementing EU policies.

alternatives to animal testing.DEF: development and implementation of test methods that avoid the use of live animals

principle of double jeopardy.DEF: right not to be tried or punished twice in criminal proceedings for the same criminal offence

food chain.DEF: sequence of organisms in which each organism provides food for the next organism

open educational resources.DEF: Teaching, learning or research materials that are in the public domain or released with an intellectual property licence that allows for free use, adaptation and distribution.

rainbow family.DEF: family where at least one parent is lesbian, gay, bisexual, pansexual, transgender, gender diverse, intersex, non-binary, queer or asexual

comic book.DEF: A series of drawings published or done for publication and presenting a narrative, which may or may not be humorous.

EU Intelligence and Situation Centre.DEF: intelligence body of the External Action Service (EEAS) which is the exclusive civilian intelligence function of the European Union that provides in-depth analysis for EU decision makers

food-borne disease.DEF: A disease caused by consuming food or drinking water contaminated by pathogenic (disease-causing) micro-organisms such as bacteria and their toxins, viruses and parasites.

rail safety.DEF: Efficiency and reliability of railway services.

prosumer.DEF: individual who both consumes and produces the same product or service

presumption of innocence.DEF: principle according to which everyone who has been charged shall be presumed innocent until proved guilty according to law

European territorial cooperation.DEF: Objective financed by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) that supports cross-border, transnational and interregional cooperation programmes.

blended finance.DEF: instrument for achieving EU external policy objectives that combines EU grants with loans or equity from public and private financiers

non-motorised transport.DEF: non-motorised forms of transport involving physical activity, such as walking and cycling

clientelism.DEF: exchange of goods and services for political support

EU candidate countries.DEF: Applicant countries for European Union membership.  Candidate country status does not give a right to join the Union automatically.

genetic database.DEF: Database devoted to knowledge about specific genes and gene products.

family reunification.DEF: Entry into and residence in a Member State by family members of a third country national residing lawfully in that Member State in order to preserve the family unit, whether the family relationship arose before or after the resident's entry.

Economic and Financial Committee.DEF: Consultative body set up on 1 January 1998 under Article 134 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU), which contributes to the preparation of the work of the Ecofin Council.

maintenance staff.DEF: personnel responsible for repairs, maintenance and general upkeep of facilities

data science.DEF: multi-disciplinary field that uses scientific methods, processes, algorithms and systems to extract knowledge and insights from data in various forms, both structured and unstructured

Southern neighbourhood.DEF: EU cooperation, in the framework of the European Neighbourhood Policy (ENP), with ten partner countries: Algeria, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Palestine*, Syria and Tunisia.

whistleblowing.DEF: Whistleblowing is bringing into the open information on activities that have harmed or threaten the public interest.

Health Emergency Preparedness and Respon.DEF: EU body that aims to enable the EU and its Member States to prepare and rapidly deploy the necessary medical countermeasures in the event of serious cross-border health threats by covering the whole value chain from conception to distribution and use

virtual currency.DEF: Digital representation of value, not issued by a central bank, credit institution or e-money institution, which in some circumstances can be used as an alternative to money.

e-Health.DEF: Use of information and communication technologies for health and well-being.

invasive species.DEF: Species that are not native to a particular ecosystem and whose introduction and spread cause, or are likely to cause, socio-cultural, economic or environmental harm or harm to human health.

geo-blocking.DEF: Practice of preventing access to websites, applications and media based on user's geographical location.

e-procurement.DEF: Use of electronic communications by public sector organisations when buying supplies and services or tendering public works.

financial transparency.DEF: Refers to comprehensive, consistent and accessible information on public finances.

body mass index.DEF: Measure of a person’s weight relative to height.

legal tech.DEF: use of technology and software to support and provide services to the legal or economic sector or the actors and companies active in it

biocide.DEF: Active substance and preparation intended to destroy, deter, render harmless, prevent the action of, or otherwise exert a controlling effect on any harmful organism by chemical or biological means.

crowdfunding.DEF: An emerging alternative form of financing that connects those who can give, lend or invest money directly with those who need financing for a specific project. It usually refers to public online calls to contribute finance to specific projects.

radicalisation.DEF: Process by which a person adopts radical positions on political or social issues.

municipal waste.DEF: Mixed waste and separately collected waste from households and from other sources, where such waste is similar in nature and composition to waste from households.

Bologna Process.DEF: mechanism promoting intergovernmental cooperation between 48 European countries in the field of higher education

intimidation lawsuit.DEF: lawsuits intended to censor, intimidate, and silence critics by burdening them with the cost of a legal defense until they abandon their criticism or opposition

machine learning.DEF: Application of artificial intelligence (AI) that provides systems the ability to automatically learn and improve from experience without being explicitly programmed.

financial stability.DEF: The condition in which the financial system — comprising financial intermediaries, markets and market infrastructures — is capable of withstanding shocks and the unravelling of financial imbalances, thereby mitigating the likelihood of disruptions in the financial intermediation process which are severe enough to significantly impair the allocation of savings to profitable investment opportunities.

heatwave.DEF: extended period of abnormally hot weather relative to the expected conditions of the area at that time of year, which may be accompanied by high humidity

landslide.DEF: Form of mass wasting that includes a wide range of ground movements, such as rockfalls, deep-seated slope failures, mudflows and debris flows

risk management.DEF: Coordinated activity to direct and control an organisation with regard to risk.

language industry.DEF: Sector comprising translation, interpreting, subtitling and dubbing, language technology tools development and linguistic consultancy.

pricing of medicines.DEF: Act of setting a price for a medicine and covering the cost through a 3rd-party payer (such as social health insurance or the national health service).

think tank.DEF: A group or an institution organised for intensive research and solving of problems, especially in the areas of technology, social or political strategy or armament.

strategic partnership (EU).DEF: partnership between the European Union and third countries that promotes international cooperation in a range of areas including the economy, security, and environmental issues

cash changeover.DEF: Change from one currency to another for cash payments.

cloud computing.DEF: Storing, processing and use of data on remotely located computers accessed over the internet.

information technology incident.DEF: unexpected event that disrupts or otherwise has an adverse impact on the intended behaviour or operation of information systems or services

compliance audit.DEF: Compliance audit deals with the degree to which the audited entity follows rules, laws and regulation, policies, established codes or agreed terms and conditions, etc.

product recall.DEF: request to return to the maker a batch or an entire production run of a product, usually due to the discovery of safety issues

food security.DEF: Food security exists when all people have, at all times, physical, social and economic access to sufficient, safe and nutritious food that meets their dietary energy requirements and food preferences for an active and healthy life.

food systems.DEF: interconnected systems and processes that influence nutrition, food, health, community development and agriculture

policymaking.DEF: Process by which governments or organisations translate their political vision into programmes and actions as a basis for delivering results and for making decisions.

office space.DEF: building or part of a building that can be used as an office

business continuity.DEF: ability of an organisation to continue to function even after a disastrous event

cash-in-transit.DEF: Transport, storage and handling services of banknotes and coins for credit institutions.

public procurement.DEF: Process whereby public authorities acquire works, supplies or services by one or more contracting authorities from economic operators chosen by those contracting authorities.

water quality.DEF: A graded value of the components (organic and inorganic, chemical or physical) which comprise the nature of water.

adequacy decision (EU).DEF: Decision which establishes that a non-EU country (third country or international organisation) ensures an adequate level of protection of personal data.

macro-financial assistance.DEF: A programme to assist non-EU countries covered by the European neighbourhood policy that have an International Monetary Fund programme.

European Maritime and Fisheries Fund.DEF: Fund for the EU’s maritime and fisheries policies for the period 2014-2020.

information warfare.DEF: The offensive and defensive use of information and information systems to deny, exploit, corrupt or destroy an adversary’s information, information-based processes, information systems and computer-based networks while protecting one’s own.

health technology.DEF: Technology applying knowledge and skills in the form of devices, medicines, vaccines, procedures and systems developed to solve health problems.

community resilience.DEF: Capacity of a system, community or society potentially exposed to hazards to cope with external stress and disturbances from social, political or environmental change, by resisting or learning from past disasters for a better future protection and risk reduction in order to reach and maintain an acceptable level of functioning and structure.

European Solidarity Corps.DEF: Supports young people's participation in various forms of voluntary activities, both within and outside the European Union.

radio frequency identification.DEF: Technology used for tracking objects, people or animals through a tag emitting radio waves.

gastronomy.DEF: study of the relationship between food and culture

energy poverty.DEF: inability of households to ensure their energy needs, and it is linked to a combination of factors

pollinator.DEF: insect or other agent that conveys pollen to a plant and so allows fertilization

sustainable finance.DEF: mobilisation of finance to integrate environmental, social and governance criteria into business or investment decisions, leading to sustainable growth and the transition to a climate-neutral economy

international humanitarian law.DEF: A set of rules that seeks to limit the effects of armed conflict on civilians. This law defines the right to receive humanitarian assistance, protection of civilians including medical and humanitarian workers, and the protection rights of refugees, prisoners and the wounded and sick.

gender identity.DEF: According to Institute of gender equality (EIGE),  gender identity refers to each person’s deeply felt internal and individual experience of gender, which may or may not correspond with the sex assigned at birth, including the personal sense of the body (which may involve, if freely chosen, modification of bodily appearance or function by medical, surgical or other means) and other expressions of gender, including dress, speech and mannerisms.

monetary income.DEF: Income accruing to the National Central Banks in the performance of the monetary policy function.

critical infrastructure security.DEF: Protection of systems, networks and assets whose continuous operation is deemed necessary to ensure the security of a State, its economy, and the public’s health and safety.

age-sensitive aid.DEF: Humanitarian aid operations that integrate age as a matter of quality and effective programming.

maladministration.DEF: intentional or unintentional failure to carry out administrative duties and responsibilities properly and fully

photonics.DEF: The science of generating, controlling and detecting light.

EU strategy.DEF: Political directions and priority areas for longer-term EU actions used as a basis for the European Commission's Work Programme and for legislative and non-legislative initiatives.

smart technology.DEF: Technology that uses artificial intelligence, machine learning, and big data analysis to provide cognitive awareness to objects (IoT) that were in the past considered inanimate.

business model.DEF: Method or means by which a company tries to capture value from its business.

crisis management.DEF: Discipline incorporating managerial, organisational and technical facilities to assist in managing the return to normal life in the case of a major incident as quickly and swiftly as possible.

Pacific Alliance.DEF: Regional integration initiative created on April 28, 2011 by Chile, Colombia, Mexico and Peru.

member of the Committee of the Regions.DEF: Any representative of a regional or local body who has been appointed as such by the Council in accordance with the proposal of her/his Member State.

substance of human origin.DEF: umbrella term for blood and blood components, tissues and cells, organs and other therapeutic and diagnostic substances of human origin

open data.DEF: Practice of publishing (raw) data in a way that is accessible, reusable, machine readable and licensed permissively. Can be generated by a wide range of parties, including public authorities, the semi-public sector, businesses and the public.

social enterprise.DEF: Operator in the social economy whose main objective is to have a social impact rather than make a profit for their owners or shareholders.

country of origin principle.DEF: principle according to which a service provider is subject only to the law of the country in which it is established and Member States may not restrict services from a provider established in another Member State

patient safety.DEF: Absence of preventable harm to a patient during the process of health care.

novel food.DEF: Type of food that does not have a significant history of consumption or is produced by a method that has not previously been used for food.

urban statistics.DEF: Provides data covering most aspects relating to quality of life in cities.

unaccompanied child.DEF: Minor who is outside their country of origin and separated from both parents or their previous legal / customary primary caregiver.

glacier.DEF: large mass of perennial ice that originates on land by the recrystallization of snow or other forms of solid precipitation and that shows evidence of past or present flow

visit to EU institutions.DEF: visits by citizens to the seats of EU institutions

transitional justice.DEF: Refers to the set of judicial and non-judicial measures that have been implemented by different countries in order to redress the legacies of massive human rights abuses.

EU study report.DEF: Report financed by the EU budget to support EU institutions when shaping new legislation or policy.

illegal logging.DEF: Illegal logging takes place when timber is harvested, transported, bought or sold in violation of national laws.

Eastern Partnership.DEF: Joint initiative launched in 2009 between the EU and its eastern European partners (Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Georgia, the Republic of Moldova and Ukraine).

digital transformation.DEF: profound transformation of business activities, competencies, and business models to fully leverage the opportunities of digital technologies

artificial neural network.DEF: Deep learning computational data model from artificial intelligence capable of pattern recognition and machine learning, based on the structure and functions of biological neural network.

micro-credential.DEF: qualification evidencing learning outcomes acquired through a short, transparently-assessed course or module

endocrine disruptor.DEF: Substances in our environment, food and consumer products that can disrupt endocrine systems and wildlife and result in adverse health effects.

natural language processing.DEF: A field of computer science, artificial intelligence, and linguistics concerned with the interactions between computers and human (natural) languages.

musculoskeletal disorder.DEF: Injuries or pain in the human musculoskeletal system, including the joints, ligaments, muscles, nerves, tendons, and structures that support limbs, neck and back.

drone.DEF: Unmanned or remote piloted aircraft used for military or civil usage.

collaborative economy.DEF: Economic system where activities and services are facilitated by collaborative online platforms that create an open marketplace for the temporary usage of goods or services often provided by private individuals.

cyber-bullying.DEF: form of bullying or harassment using electronic means

augmented reality.DEF: technology that superimposes a computer-generated image on a user's view of the real world, thus providing a composite view

high-performance computing.DEF: computing system with extremely high computational power

energy audit.DEF: Procedure to define the energy consumption and to identify energy saving opportunities for a building/group of buildings/process/system.

economic governance (EU).DEF: A system of institutions and procedures established with a view to achieving Union objectives in the economic field, more specifically the coordination of economic policies to promote economic and social progress for the EU and its citizens.

International Accounting Standards.DEF: set of internationally-agreed principles and procedures relating to the way that companies present their accounts

Arab world.DEF: collective term for the Arabic-speaking countries and the geographical and cultural region as defined by the World Bank

Danube region.DEF: Covers nine EU Member States (Austria, Bulgaria, Croatia, Czech Republic, Germany, Hungary, Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia), three accession countries (Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro and Serbia) and two neighbourhood countries (Moldova and Ukraine).

digital single market.DEF: An area where people and businesses can freely access and exercise online activities under conditions of fair competition, regardless of their nationality or where they live.

smart specialisation.DEF: policy approach whereby countries or regions identify and select a limited number of priority areas for knowledge-based investments, focusing on their strengths and comparative advantages

financial stress test.DEF: risk management and supervisory tool used by financial institutions, micro-prudential and macro-prudential supervisors to explore vulnerabilities and assess the resilience of financial institutions (e.g. banks, insurers) and whole systems (e.g. the banking sector, the insurance sector) to severe but plausible external shocks

transposition deficit.DEF: Gap between EU directives adopted and effective implementation by the Member States.

3D printing.DEF: Process of printing three-dimensional solid objects from a digital file by placing material on top of each other in layers.

national competent authority.DEF: organisation that has the legally delegated or invested authority, or power to perform a designated function, normally monitoring compliance with the national statutes and regulations

web analytics.DEF: measurement, collection, analysis and reporting of web data to understand and optimize web usage

green economy.DEF: Economic system that results in improved human well-being and social equity, while significantly reducing environmental risks and ecological scarcities.

cognitive skills.DEF: brain-based skills we need to carry out any task from the simplest to the most complex which have more to do with the mechanisms of how we learn, remember, problem-solve, and pay attention

Arctic Council.DEF: Leading intergovernmental forum promoting cooperation, coordination and interaction on common Arctic issues, in particular on issues of sustainable development and environmental protection in the Arctic.

Treaty on Stability, Coordination and Go.DEF: The treaty deals with three main issues: fiscal stability, economic coordination and convergence, and governance of the euro area. It requires euro area Member States to strengthen fiscal discipline through a balanced budget rule and an automatic correction mechanism. It also formalises the holding of Euro Summit meetings and the role of the President of the Euro Summit.

ontology.DEF: formal representation of phenomena of a universe of discourse with an underlying vocabulary including definitions and axioms that make the intended meaning explicit and describe phenomena and their interrelationships

drug residue.DEF: Maximum permitted level of residues of certain substances — such as pesticides or veterinary medical products — in foodstuffs.

financial technology.DEF: Technology to support financial or banking services.

spatial data.DEF: any data with a direct or indirect reference to a specific location or geographical area

personal mobility device.DEF: class of compact, motorised micromobility vehicle for transporting an individual at speeds that do not normally exceed 25 km/h (16 mph)

anonymisation.DEF: Processing of personal data in such a manner that the personal data can no longer be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of additional information, provided that such additional information is kept separately and is subject to technical and organisational measures to ensure that the personal data are not attributed to an identified or identifiable natural person.

research infrastructure.DEF: Facilities, resources and services used by the science community to conduct research and foster innovation.

South China Sea question.DEF: Disputes regarding the freedom of navigation and international commerce in the South China Sea.

antimicrobial resistance.DEF: AMR is the ability of microorganisms (e.g. bacteria, viruses or parasites, such as the malaria parasite) to resist antimicrobial treatments, especially antibiotics.

data governance.DEF: set of processes, policies, standards, and guidelines that organizations use to manage, enhance and protect their data assets

UCITS fund.DEF: An investment fund regulated at European level in accordance with the UCITS Directive (85/611/EEC). Once registered in any EU Member State, a UCITS fund can be freely marketed across the EU.

Indo-Pacific region.DEF: geopolitical area that spans two regions of the Indian Ocean and the Pacific Ocean

coronavirus disease.DEF: Disease caused by members of the coronavirus (CoV) family.

agreement on government procurement.DEF: Plurilateral agreement of the World Trade Organization aiming to mutually open government procurement markets among its parties.

collective memory.DEF: Common memory of a group of people which may be passed down from one generation to the next, and which provides a basis from which the group can derive an awareness of its unity or peculiarity.

ecological\u00a0footprint.DEF: Measures the extent to which the ecological demand of human economies stays within or exceeds the capacity of the biosphere to supply goods and services.

5G.DEF: Fifth generation of mobile network telecommunications technologies.

shadow banking.DEF: A system of credit intermediation that involves entities and activities outside the regular banking system.

nature-based solution.DEF: solutions inspired and supported by nature, which are cost-effective, simultaneously provide environmental, social and economic benefits and help build resilience

interreligious dialogue.DEF: Open and respectful exchange of views between individuals and groups belonging to different  religions, spiritual and humanistic world traditions.

financial literacy.DEF: Financial literacy is the understanding of various financial areas including topics related to managing personal finance, money, borrowing, investing.

energy transition.DEF: fundamental structural change in an energy system at national or global level

staff regulations (EU).DEF: Staff regulations of officials of the European Union and the conditions of employment of other servants of the European Union.

EU energy label.DEF: label providing clear and simple indications of a product's energy efficiency intended to be a key driver for helping consumers choose products which are more energy efficient

economics profession.DEF: Professionals, who conduct research, monitor data, analyse information and prepare reports and plans to resolve economic and business problems and develop models to analyse, explain and forecast economic behaviour and patterns.

withdrawal from the EU.DEF: Legal and political process whereby an EU Member state exercises its right under the Treaty on European Union to cease to be a member of the Union.

EU direct payments.DEF: Payments under the common agricultural policy granted directly to farmers in the form of a basic income support, decoupled from production and stabilising their income stemming from sales on the markets, which are subject to volatility.

sea level rise.DEF: increase in the level of the world’s oceans due to the effects of global warming
